(67, 1, '2015-08-07 11:25:08', '2015-08-07 08:25:08', 'The winners for Devpost’s (formerly ChallengePost) Summer Jam have been announced officially and I want to thank all the developers who submitted for our “Maps as Art” challenge. For this challenge, hackers were asked to reimagine the world around you through an interactive mapping web/mobile application or hardware hack. Participants who created the best “wall worthy” interactive map received an Apple Watch. While there were many excellent submissions to choose from, we could only pick one winner.\r\n\r\nThe first place prize went to the team of Nick Vernij, Lem Severein, Sufi Gaffar and Daniel Mizrachi for “Underground map” which can be seen <a href="http://devpost.com/software/underground-map-pxy6qd" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a>. This team from The Netherlands and the United Kingdom created a detailed map of a world people normally don''t see. Using open source and open data, the team of teenagers loaded data about underground cables, pipelines and tunnels into our Clusterpoint cloud-based database to create the map.\r\n\r\nMore about the winning team members:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Nick is a 16-year-old developer and student from Rotterdam who has been building web sites since he was 12. He mostly codes in PhP, Javascript and Java.</li>\r\n	<li>Lem is also 16 years old and a student from Rotterdam. He is skilled in CSS, HTML, Javascript and PhP.</li>\r\n	<li>Sufi is a 17-year-old web developer - proficient in programming languages - and student from London who is open to learning new skills.</li>\r\n	<li>Daniel is also 17 and a web developer and student from London. He loves open data and APIs.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs part of the prize, each member of the team received an Apple Watch! If you want to view the map in greater detail, visit the solution <a href="http://underground.nickforall.nl/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a>. The team recommends using Chrome for maximum performance given the massive size of the dataset.\r\n\r\nWe also want to recognize two more outstanding submissions:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://devpost.com/software/wikimap-lv79s5" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">WikiMap</a> – This map, created by Michael Sopinka and Chris Buttenham, lets you view your world through Google Maps and StreetView. The team used ClusterPoint on the back-end to host latitudinal and longitudinal data from Wikipedia along with ClusterPoint''s GeoSpatial search. Try it out for yourself here.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://devpost.com/software/money-man" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Money-Man</a> – This hack was created in one week by Edgar Wang. This tool maps out unclaimed security deposits in Toronto. What inspired Edgar to develop this tool is that fact that people love to complain about how “the government takes their money.” But the reality is Toronto is trying to give it back, and no one is claiming it! This hack uses Clusterpoint’s REST API to request data from the City of Toronto’s OpenData initiative and Clusterpoint’s cloud-based database to store the data. You can try it out <a href="http://edgarr.me/Money-Man/" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThanks again to all of you who submitted for our “Map as Art” hackathon.', 'Review of Devpost Summer Jam Hackathon', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'review-of-devpost-summer-jam-hackathon', '', '', '2016-01-29 11:31:33', '2016-01-29 09:31:33', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?p=67', 15, 'post', '', 0),
