INSERT INTO `cp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(27, 1, '2015-12-22 15:54:33', '2015-12-22 13:54:33', 'Maps have been very valuable to mankind since ancient times. At the beginning people had to look up to the sky and stars were their pointers. Then cartography brought us possibility to visit nearby places and sometimes even mystical parts of the world by looking at the maps. Nowadays maps are everywhere and we could not imagine our lives without some mapping solutions. We depend on maps when we drive, when we are traveling and looking for new and interesting places to stop by.\r\n<!--more-->\r\nMajority of maps are proprietary. We are limited in what we can do with them. And it’s more impossible than not to extract just portion of data. We need to use what we are given, even if it comes with user tracking and advertisements. Not everyone likes such lock in. That’s where crowdsourced, open data comes in. One of such data sets is OpenStreetMap (OSM).\r\n\r\nEven though a lot of people think, that OSM is only a map, which is visible when you visit <a href="http://openstreetmap.org/" target="_blank">openstreetmap.org</a>, it''s actually much more than that. OSM is a big data set and particular map is just one of many representations of this data. One subset of OSM data is <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Points_of_interest" target="_blank">Points of interest</a> (POI). If you want to create some mapping services which would display POI data, you have several options:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Use <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Xapi" target="_blank">OSM Xapi</a>. This way you can access most up to date data. However this API is not suited for heavy usage. API tends to be slow and is rate limited.</li>\r\n	<li>You can download whole OSM data dump (called <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Planet.osm" target="_blank">planet.osm</a>) and process it with <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Osmosis">Osmosis</a>. That way you could extract data that you actually need, import it in your DB of choice and use it. This option will not be suited for most developers, because it requires extensive knowledge of the tools and very good hardware to handle big data dumps.</li>\r\n	<li>You can use service like MapQuest. Their <a href="https://developer.mapquest.com/products/spatial-search/" target="_blank">Search API</a> provides possibility to fetch POI data. However their free tier only allows 500 requests per day which might not be enough for you. You can either upgrade to paid plan or check out 4th option in our list.</li>\r\n	<li>You can use OSM POI db provided by <a href="http://clusterpoint.com/" target="_blank">Clusterpoint Cloud</a>. Yes, that''s right! We host extracted OpenStretMap Points of interest data and it''s available to anyone. We are covering all associated storage costs! Users are charged only for CPU power used to retrieve data. However thank''s to our generous <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/pricing" target="_blank">Free tier</a> you will be able to perform lots and lots of queries before coming close to Free CPU limit. Which means that OSM POI data queries for majority of you will be completely free of charge!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOSM POI data and Clusterpoint Cloud is a perfect match. By using our scalable infrastructure we can guarantee that your requests will always be handled very fast. Clusterpoint''s support for unstructured data documents, 2D &amp; 3D Geo-spatial indexing and Full-text search allows it''s users to create very feature rich applications. This tutorial is first in series about our public OSM POI database. You will learn about database structure and how to perform basic queries. In future tutorials we will go through more complex examples to explore different features and Clusterpoint server.\r\n<h2>Tutorial structure</h2>\r\nThis tutorial is first in series about how to use OpenStreetMap POI data and different Geo related features of Clusterpoint server. We will learn about OSM POI db access, how to build search queries, how to search within shapes and how to do basic aggregations. In each section we will look at separate functions and classes. At the end we will put together everything we have learned and will assemble code needed for demo application.\r\n<h2>OSM POI database</h2>\r\nTo get access to OSM POI database you first need to <a href="https://cloud.clusterpoint.com/#authentication/signup" target="_blank">sign up</a> for Clusterpoint Cloud account. It’s free of charge. After sign in click on Public databases.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-188" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ccloud_1.png" alt="ccloud_1" width="798" height="102" />\r\n\r\nthen on pulic::osm_poi\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-187" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ccloud_2.png" alt="ccloud_2" width="807" height="213" />\r\n\r\nTo actually browse around data click on Query button. This will open query window with first 20 objects.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-186" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ccloud_3.png" alt="ccloud_3" width="797" height="189" />\r\n\r\nThere are many fields in each document. However in this tutorial we will be taking closer look at just a few of them.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>id</strong> - this is object''s ID. It corresponds to real OSM object ID. You can confirm that by opening URL <code>http://api.openstreetmap.org/api/0.6/[type]/[id]</code> in your Web browser. Replace [id] with value from id field and [type] with value from type field.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>lat</strong> - object''s Latitude</li>\r\n	<li><strong>lon</strong> - object''s Longitude</li>\r\n	<li><strong>tags</strong> - object''s <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Tags" target="_blank">tags </a>. Tags are very useful as they give meaning to the data. They describe what particular object really represents. Each object can have many tags. Even though there are guidelines on how to set up tags, there are no strict rules about that. As a result it''s not uncommon that some objects are missing very valuable tags. Some similar objects are described with different tags etc. Because of that it''s sometimes complex to filter and group such data. However relative freedom in tags is what makes OSM data so unique and valuable.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you are using OSM POI data in your projects, make sure to put correct copyright notice wherever you display data:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n© &lt;a href="http://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright" target="_blank"&gt;OpenStreetMap contributors&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>OSM POI access from API</h2>\r\nTo access OSM POI data from scripts we will be using Clusterpoint’s <a href="https://github.com/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">PHP client library</a>. There are libraries for <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/docs/?page=API_Library_Downloads" target="_blank">other languages too</a>. Consult documentation about how to download and set up one that’s suited for your environment. It should be easy to translate PHP examples to other languages. However if you run into problems, you can always refer to <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/docs/?page=Reference">Reference</a> where it’s shown how to do the same thing in various languages.\r\n\r\nYou can download <a href="https://github.com/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">PHP Client from Github</a> or you can use <a href="http://getcomposer.org/" target="_blank">Composer</a>. In case of Composer you will need to require clusterpoint/php-client-api from <a href="https://packagist.org/packages/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">Packagist</a>. Keep in mind that default version for download (at the moment of writing) is 3.0 which is a bit outdated. To get most up to date version require "dev-master".\r\n\r\nTo access public::osm_poi database from PHP we need to create a connection\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$cps_connection = new CPS_Connection(\r\n                            new CPS_LoadBalancer([\r\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-0.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\r\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-1.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\r\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-2.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\r\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-3.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\r\n                                ]),\r\n                            ''public::osm_poi'',\r\n                            ''USERNAME'',\r\n                            ''PASSWORD'',\r\n                            ''document'', ''//document/id'',\r\n                            [''account'' =&gt; ''ACCOUNT_ID'']\r\n    );\r\n</code></pre>\r\nReplace USERNAME with your username, PASSWORD with your password and ACCOUNT_ID with your account id. Even though it’s possible to use the same username and password which you use to log into Clusterpoint Cloud UI panel, we strongly recommend to create separate user with access to only this database. Consult <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/docs/?page=Authorisation" target="_blank">documentation</a> on how to create a new user.\r\n\r\nIn LoadBalancer I have specified connection through SSL. That’s the recommended type of connection. However if for some reason you can not use SSL replace <i>tcps</i> with <i>tcp</i> and change port from <i>9008</i> to <i>9007</i>.\r\n<h2>Shape definitions</h2>\r\nIn Clusterpoint it’s very easy to use search within shapes. There are two supported types of shapes: polygons and circles. It’s possible to use several shapes in one request. By combining shapes you can support very complex Geo queries. This time we will look only on how to search within a circle. In next tutorial we will go through various shape combinations (separate shapes, intersecting ones etc.).\r\n\r\nAll queries involving shapes should consist of two parts: shape definition and usage of said shape. To define circle in PHP use CPS_CircleDefinition:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$circle = CPS_CircleDefinition(''circle'', [$lat, $lng], ''1 km'', ''lat'', ''lon'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIn first parameter you should pass identificator for particular circle. I used "circle", but it could have been "bigcircle" or anything else. Second is array of latitude and longitude. Third is radius of the circle. To set radius in miles use <i>mi</i> instead of <i>km</i>. Last two parameters are names of latitude and longitude fields in db.\r\n\r\nOnce circle is defined we can use it in search query.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term('' &gt;&lt;circle'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nThis query tells server to look for objects which are inside of circle. <code>&lt;&gt;</code> would tell to look outside of circle. Notice that you should leave one empty space before <code>&lt;&gt;</code> and <code>&gt;&lt;</code> operators. If we would have used "bigcircle" in first parameter for circle definition, then search query would be <code>&gt;&lt;bigcircle</code>.\r\n\r\nWhen we will create search request we will need to use previously defined <code>$circle</code> to add circle definition to search request (you will see that further in tutorial).\r\n<strong>Tip:</strong> if there are some shapes which you use very often and do not want to send shape definitions with each request you can define shapes in database configuration. However that’s not possible with public::osm_poi database. But know that such option is available if you ever need that in your other databases.\r\n<h2>Search within tags</h2>\r\nOne of useful OSM POI tags is <i>amenity</i>. It can be used to group and filter objects by their type. For example, if you want to look for Cafes, you can use\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term(''cafe'', ''tags/amenity'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nif you want to find any object which have amenity cafe or bar:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term(''{ cafe bar }'', ''tags/amenity'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIn case of OSM POI we know that values of tags do not have empty spaces. If there were values with empty spaces in them, you would need to use double quotes (ASCII 34) to contain phrase. Example:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term(''{ cafe "fast food" bar } '', ''tags/amenity'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nOne last thing. Not all objects have amenity tag. That’s why you might want to search objects for which amenity tag does not exist. To do that you need to use "does not exist" operator:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term(''=""'', ''tags/amenity'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nOf course you can combine <code class="php">=""</code> with other values. This example will search for objects which have amenity tag equal to cafe or amenity tag is not set up at all.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term(''{ ="" cafe }'', ''tags/amenity'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Aggregation</h2>\r\nClusterpoint server allows to perform different types of aggregations. In this tutorial we will perform only one simple aggregation. More complex examples will be demonstrated in future tutorials. We again return to amenity tag. To show amenities filter in our application we need to get distinct <i>tags/amenity</i> values. Aggregation query for that is straight forward:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$aggregate = ''DISTINCT tags.amenity'';\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIt is possible to send several aggregations within one request. That saves script-server roundtrips.\r\n<h2>Search request</h2>\r\nWe have now learned how to write search query and how to write aggregation query. But those queries alone can’t do much. We need to send them to the Clusterpoint Cloud. To do that CPS_SearchRequest should be used:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term(''hotel''); // search in whole document for hotel\r\n$query .= CPS_Term('' &gt;&lt;circle''); // search within circle\r\n$offset = 0;\r\n$docs = 50;\r\n$search_request = new CPS_SearchRequest($query, $offset, $docs);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nFirst parameter is search query. Second is offset, but third is how many documents to return. This query will look within circle for objects that in any tag have value "hotel" in them. Query will return first 50 objects.\r\nWhen search request is instantiated we can do a bit more setup. First thing is to tell which fields we want to be returned. We want whole documents, that’s why\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$search_request-&gt;setParam(''list'', ''&lt;document&gt;yes&lt;/document&gt;'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nshould be used. Circle was used in the query. Because of that circle definitions should be added to the request:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$search_request-&gt;setShape($circle);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIt is possible to set up aggregation in the same request:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$search_request-&gt;setAggregate($aggregate);\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<h2>Response</h2>\r\nOnce search request is constructed we can send search request to the server and in return we can get response with objects that matched search query. As well as aggregation result.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$search_response = $cps_connection-&gt;sendRequest($search_request);</code></pre>\r\nResponse objects have several useful helpers:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><code class="php">$search_response-&gt;getHits()</code> - count of matched objects</li>\r\n	<li><code class="php">$search_response-&gt;getFrom()</code> - offset that was used in search query</li>\r\n	<li><code class="php">$search_response-&gt;getTo()</code> - number of last element</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTo get actual matched documents use getDocuments:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nforeach ($search_response-&gt;getDocuments() as $id =&gt; $document) {\r\n// perform some actions with documents\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\nBy default documents are returned as SimpleXML. To override that you can pass constant:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>DOC_TYPE_ARRAY</strong> - to get array</li>\r\n	<li><strong>DOC_TYPE_STDCLASS</strong> - to get std class</li>\r\n	<li><strong>DOC_TYPE_SIMPLEXML</strong> - to get simplexml</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTo get data from aggregation you need to use <code>getAggregate()</code>\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$aggregated_data = $search_response-&gt;getAggregate(DOC_TYPE_ARRAY);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIn this example aggregation data will be returned as array. As it’s possible to send several aggregation queries in one request <code>$aggregated_data</code> will hold response from all aggregations. At index 0 you will get data for first aggregation, at index 1 for second etc.\r\n<h2>Demo application</h2>\r\nLet’s put together everything we have learned today and build fully functional application. This demo application will allow to look up objects in specific section of the map, will allow to find objects by search phrase and filter objects by Amenity tag. By click on map marker it will be possible to view all tags of particular object.\r\n\r\nFor demo application I have used few very useful tools:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>UI is built by using CSS from <a href="http://getbootstrap.com/" target="_blank">Bootstrap</a> framework. On JS part <a href="https://jquery.com/" target="_blank">jQuery</a> was used. Both of them are very well known among developers and are de-facto standards.</li>\r\n	<li>On server side Clusterpoint <a href="https://github.com/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">PHP Client</a> is used. As well as <a href="http://www.slimframework.com/" target="_blank">Slim framework</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>For mapping solution Google Maps API was chosen. It’s very common to see OSM POI data on maps generated from OSM data. However that’s not some sort of requirement. It’s perfectly valid to use Google Maps in combination with OSM POI data. Keep in mind that if you are using mapping solution which is not built from OSM data, you might run into situation when POI object is shown in the middle of the street or not near a street at all (it''s possible that OSM have roads which are not depicted on Google Maps).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nDo no worry if you are not familiar with some of used tools. If you have basic programming knowledge, you should be able to follow through.\r\n\r\nYou can access source code of demo app at <a href="https://github.com/Endijs/osm-poi-clusterpoint-cloud-demo-part1" target="_blank">https://github.com/Endijs/osm-poi-clusterpoint-cloud-demo-part1</a> and you can view live application demo at <a href="http://osmpoi.endijs.com/" target="_blank">http://osmpoi.endijs.com</a>. If you want to set up application on your own server follow Installation notes in <code>readme.md</code> file.\r\n\r\nThis demo application have only 1 file which handles all communication with Clusterpoint Cloud. Let’s take a look at it ( /public/index.php ) and discuss main parts of it.\r\nAt the beginning we require Composer’s autoload file and some configuration files.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nrequire_once ''../vendor/autoload.php'';\r\nrequire_once ''../cfg/cps.php'';\r\nrequire_once ''../cfg/google.php'';\r\n</code></pre>\r\nSlim framework application gets instantiated\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$app = new \\Slim\\Slim([\r\n        ''debug''          =&gt; false,\r\n        ''templates.path'' =&gt; ''../templates'',\r\n        ''cps''            =&gt; $cps_config,\r\n        ''google''         =&gt; $google_config,\r\n    ]\r\n);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nRoute to index page. Configuration about Google Maps API is retrieved and Maps API key gets assigned to the view. And then template gets rendered.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$app-&gt;get(''/'', function() use ($app) {\r\n    $google_config = $app-&gt;config(''google'');\r\n    $app-&gt;view-&gt;setData(''maps_api_key'', $google_config[''maps_api_key'']);\r\n    $app-&gt;render(''index.php'');\r\n});\r\n</code></pre>\r\nThis route handles all Ajax requests from applications UI.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$app-&gt;get("/api/list/:lat/:lng/:radius/*", function ($lat, $lng, $radius) use ($app) {\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\nCast data types for mandatory fields and retrieve optional request values.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$lat = (float)$lat;\r\n$lng = (float)$lng;\r\n$radius = (int)$radius;\r\n$q = trim((string)$app-&gt;request-&gt;get(''q'', '''')); // search phrase\r\n$amenities = (array)$app-&gt;request-&gt;get(''amenities'', []); // amenities filter\r\n$page = (int)$app-&gt;request-&gt;get(''page'', 1); // page\r\n</code></pre>\r\nBasic validation. In real application you should validate all input from user.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nif ($page &lt; 1) {\r\n    $page = 1;\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\nData will be returned in this structure.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$objects = [\r\n        ''total'' =&gt; 0,\r\n        ''from'' =&gt; 0,\r\n        ''to'' =&gt; 0,\r\n        ''pages'' =&gt; 0,\r\n        ''current_page'' =&gt; 0,\r\n        ''list''  =&gt; [],\r\n        ''amenities'' =&gt; [],\r\n];\r\n</code></pre>\r\nConnection to Clusterpoint Cloud gets instantiated.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$cps_connection = new CPS_Connection(\r\n                            new CPS_LoadBalancer($config[''connection'']),\r\n                            $config[''database''],\r\n                            $config[''username''],\r\n                            $config[''password''],\r\n                            ''document'', ''//document/id'',\r\n                            [''account'' =&gt; $config[''account'']]\r\n);\r\n$docs = 50;\r\n$offset = $docs * ($page - 1);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nRadius is received in meters. But Clusterpoint expects values to be in km.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$radius = $radius / 1000;\r\n</code></pre>\r\nShape (circle) definition. This will need to be attached to search query.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$circle = CPS_CircleDefinition(''circle'', [$lat, $lng], $radius . '' km'', ''lat'', ''lon'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nFirst rule in search query. We are interested in objects within circle.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$query = CPS_Term('' &gt;&lt;circle'');\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIf search phrase was used, let’s add it to search query\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nif ($q !== '''') {\r\n    $query .= CPS_Term($q);\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\nAggregation query to get distinct values of amenity tag.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$aggregate = ''DISTINCT tags.amenity'';\r\n</code></pre>\r\nNow we need to process any selected amenities. We want to match any object which matches at least one amenity. That’s why all selected amenities should be placed in OR tags <code>{ }</code>. One more important thing happens here. In UI there is option to select "Amenity is not set" and value for that is - . That’s why in PHP part we need to replace "-" with "does not exist" operator <code>=""</code>.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nif (count($amenities)) {\r\n    if (array_search(''-'', $amenities) !== false) {\r\n        $amenities[array_search(''-'', $amenities)] = ''=""'';\r\n    }\r\n    $query .= CPS_Term(''{ '' . implode('' '', $amenities) . '' }'', ''tags/amenity'');\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWhen search query is created and shapes defined, we can instantiate Search Request.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$search_request = new CPS_SearchRequest($query, $offset, $docs);\r\n$search_request-&gt;setParam(''list'', ''&lt;document&gt;yes&lt;/document&gt;'');\r\n$search_request-&gt;setShape($circle);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIf no amenities were used, we can send aggregation within search request. Why can’t we send aggregation when amenity is selected? That’s because in such scenario aggregation will return exactly those selected amenities. But we want all amenities.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nif ($query_without_amenities == $query) {\r\n    $search_request-&gt;setAggregate($aggregate);\r\n}\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\nLet’s send request to the Clusterpoint Cloud.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$search_response = $cps_connection-&gt;sendRequest($search_request);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nIf response had any hits we can loop over returned documents.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nif ($search_response-&gt;getHits() &gt; 0) {\r\n    $objects[''total''] = $search_response-&gt;getHits();\r\n    $objects[''from''] = $search_response-&gt;getFrom() + 1;\r\n    $objects[''to''] = $search_response-&gt;getTo();\r\n\r\n    $objects[''pages''] = ceil($objects[''total''] / $docs);\r\n    $objects[''current_page''] = $search_response-&gt;getFrom() / $docs + 1;\r\n\r\n    foreach ($search_response-&gt;getDocuments(DOC_TYPE_ARRAY) as $id =&gt; $document) {\r\n        ksort($document[''tags'']);\r\n        $objects[''list''][] = [\r\n            ''id'' =&gt; $document[''id''],\r\n            ''tags'' =&gt; $document[''tags''],\r\n            ''lat'' =&gt; $document[''lat''],\r\n            ''lng'' =&gt; $document[''lon''],\r\n        ];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nif ($query_without_amenities == $query) {\r\n    $aggregated_data = $search_response-&gt;getAggregate(DOC_TYPE_ARRAY);\r\n}\r\nelse {\r\n    $search_request-&gt;setQuery($query_without_amenities);\r\n    $search_request-&gt;setAggregate($aggregate);\r\n    $search_response = $cps_connection-&gt;sendRequest($search_request);\r\n    $aggregated_data = $search_response-&gt;getAggregate(DOC_TYPE_ARRAY);\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\nWe sent 1 aggregation request, that’s why we are interested in values at first (zero) index. We can get that by performing<code>array_pop()</code> and then looping over data. As some objects might not have values for amenity tag, distinct will return empty space for them. I’m skipping such result, because in UI there is a special checkbox for such case. To make values more readable I’m replacing underscores with empty spaces as well as first letter gets capitalized.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$aggregated_data = array_pop($aggregated_data);\r\nforeach ($aggregated_data as $value) {\r\n    $value = array_pop($value);\r\n    if (empty($value)) {\r\n        continue;\r\n    }\r\n    $objects[''amenities''][$value] = ucfirst(str_replace(''_'', '' '', $value));\r\n}\r\nksort($objects[''amenities'']);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nAppropriate response headers and body gets set and response returned.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$app-&gt;response-&gt;headers-&gt;set(''Content-Type'', ''application/json'');\r\n$app-&gt;response-&gt;setBody(json_encode($objects));\r\nreturn $app-&gt;response;\r\n</code></pre>\r\nApplication gets executed.\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\n$app-&gt;run();\r\n</code></pre>\r\nThis is fully functional demo application. However few important things are missing from it. Error and exception handling, sorting and other features will be covered in future tutorials.', 'Easy OpenStreetMap POI maps with Clusterpoint Cloud', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'easy-openstreetmap-poi-maps-with-clusterpoint-cloud', '', '', '2016-03-03 13:26:08', '2016-03-03 11:26:08', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?post_type=tutorials&#038;p=27', 1, 'tutorials', '', 0),
