(86, 1, '2015-11-04 11:37:36', '2015-11-04 09:37:36', 'With any newer technology -- or a collection of technologies as within the NoSQL space -- successful project implementations can be challenging. Overall cost, unfamiliarity for development staff, and the difficulty in extracting business value from an investment in leading edge technology all serve as pain points conspiring to cause these kinds of projects to fail. It doesn''t have to be this way.\r\n\r\nNot all NoSQL solutions are created equal. A successful NoSQL project implementation becomes realistic when leveraging an innovative database platform with a feature set that handles those pain points preventing project success. <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/the-top-5-reasons-to-use-clusterpoint" target="_blank">Clusterpoint 4</a> is a database perfect for organizations of all sizes looking to derive business value from their data. Let''s take a closer look.\r\n<h2>Managing NoSQL Project Cost</h2>\r\nControlling project costs with any emerging technology is difficult considering the unknowns when implementing something unfamiliar to system architects, network administrators, and development staff. NoSQL initiatives are no different. The specter of cost overruns become a big worry; causing any executive team to wonder about ever seeing a return on the company''s investment.\r\n\r\nScoping a project incorrectly either leads to too much server horsepower for the amount of data or the opposite problem. Both situations are less than optimal. An organization is either paying too much for hardware provisioning, or the new NoSQL database solution is too slow and unresponsive to offer meaningful value to the business.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint offers a unique <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/pricing" target="_blank">pay-per-use</a> DBaaS model that mitigates the need for a provisioning based project cost model, giving companies the flexibility to implement a NoSQL database rightsized for their budget. Peak times are easily handled from a hardware standpoint, while periods of less usage won''t break the bank.\r\n<h2>Making a DBaaS Powerful, Easy, and Fun for Developers</h2>\r\nMany modern database platforms come with learning curves that prevent easy and fast implementation. Developers and the admin team slowly come up to speed, while the project suffers delays. The business stakeholders wonder when they are going to be able to get actionable information from the new database so they can do their jobs.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint raised eyebrows in the NoSQL space when they introduced a new query language combining traditional SQL with JavaScript. This gives developers a powerful and fun way to leverage their programming ability to write queries able to transform data into something useful for the business. This built-in computing engine is instantly scalable; handling massive amounts of data quickly and easily.\r\n\r\nAs a DBaaS, Clusterpoint runs in its own environment, with data centers located all over the globe. Instant scalability across multiple servers ensures easy access to information even during peak periods. This is all accomplished without increasing the investment in a company''s own data center and network administration team.\r\n<h2>Ensuring a Valuable Return on your Organization''s IT Investment</h2>\r\nArguably, the largest pain point for any company investing in innovative IT solutions is the difficulty in quickly realizing any business value from the expenditure. In the venerable days of mainframes -- or even the client-server era for that matter -- it could take years or even more than a decade before true ROI was achieved. This doesn''t even take into account the risks of project failure, and with it, little to no realized value.\r\n\r\nIn today''s competitive, social media-driven business landscape, the world moves at the speed of light; therefore organizations barely have months before they must see tangible results from their investments in new technology. Leveraging the "as a Service" model for databases -- as seen with Clusterpoint -- is a great way to get a bigger bang for the buck when investing in a modern database platform. The DBaaS model allows companies to accomplish more without spending on their own on-premises data center.\r\n\r\nAs noted earlier, Clusterpoint''s pay-per-use pricing model also helps to mitigate the risk involved during project implementation. A company is even able to prototype a new project at little to no cost, since Clusterpoint provides the first 10GB for <a href="https://cloud.clusterpoint.com/#/authentication/signup" target="_blank">free</a>. Ultimately, most expenses actually occur once a project is generating value.\r\n\r\nThe powerful computing engine implemented as a major new feature in Clusterpoint 4 gives developers the ability to leverage both their traditional SQL knowledge as well as JavaScript, minimizing the need for costly training.\r\n\r\nOrganizations looking to make their first foray into NoSQL a successful one need to consider Clusterpoint as their database of choice. Those pain points hampering previous deployments won''t be an issue with this state of the art DBaaS. It provides a pathway for smart businesses to stay ahead of the competition.', '3 Ways To Eliminate Software Development Pain Points With Clusterpoint', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '3-ways-to-eliminate-software-development-pain-points-with-clusterpoint', '', '', '2016-02-02 11:19:02', '2016-02-02 09:19:02', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?p=86', 9, 'post', '', 0),
(88, 1, '2015-11-11 13:38:54', '2015-11-11 11:38:54', 'Data modelling is all about understanding the world so you can make interesting inferences about it. Unfortunately, it’s not always easy to get the real world to fit nicely into a single schema for your database. Sometimes the real world is messy and changes unpredictably, and sometimes your needs and requirements as developers or project managers change. When this inevitably happens, it’s important to have a database technology that allows you the flexibility to change to meet your data modelling needs.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<h2>Why Choose Schemaless?</h2>\r\nTraditional relational databases require that developers define a strict schema with enforced data types for each column in a table. While this model can be effective for slow-to-change environments and has some performance benefits, modern developers prefer database technologies that allow them to change the data schema quickly to adapt to changing needs. Every change to the data model in a traditional setup requires writing and executing a migration script, and painstakingly plotting data transitions.\r\n\r\nCutting edge technologies like the Clusterpoint 4 database allow developers to get the best of both worlds. On the one hand, Clusterpoint offers many of the speed and data transformation capabilities of a more relational database including a wide array of index options and cardinalities as well as stricter ACID transactions for data integrity. On the other hand, by allowing documents without a schema, Clusterpoint lets you model data however you choose, and adapt and adjust your schema as time goes on. Let’s take a look at a concrete example to show just how powerful these adaptable schemas can be.\r\n<h2>Modeling Spies</h2>\r\nSuppose you want to store information for you espionage organization in a data collection. In a traditional SQL setup, you might create separate tables for your spies, data clearances, and their targets. With a flexible schema using the Clusterpoint SQL syntax, you can store all the relevant information in a single record:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nINSERT INTO spies JSON VALUE {\r\n	"name": "Homer Simpson",\r\n	"codeName” : "Jay",\r\n	"clearance" : {\r\n		"level" : 5,\r\n		"expires" : 2016\r\n	},\r\n	"active" : true,\r\n	"targets" : ["Krusty", "Smithers"]\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\nThis method has several advantages over the traditional setup. First, it’s easier for developers to reason about the document as a whole. There are no complex joins required, for example, to query for all active spies with clearance level of 3 or greater who are working on a given target.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, we can add or remove information without complicated operations for changing the table, such as migrations. If our agent screws up and we’d like to add a new supervisor restriction to their clearance, for example, we simply use an insert statement on that part of the document:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nINSERT INTO spies["15"].clearance JSON VALUE { INSERT INTO `cp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(90, 1, '2015-11-17 13:40:55', '2015-11-17 11:40:55', 'Throughout 2015, Clusterpoint has been traveling to different locations worldwide to support AngelHack (AH) hackathon participants. For those of unfamiliar with <a href="http://angelhack.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">AngelHack</a>, it is the world’s largest and most diverse global hacker community, helping to drive open innovation of tech products, platforms and brands. This year the various AngelHack series events in more than 50 cities gathered in total hundreds of teams comprised of hackers ranging in age from 8 to 56 years old. The hackers were mainly students from middle school, high school, and college as well as college graduates.\r\n<h2>Rydr</h2>\r\nDuring the entire AngelHack season, Clusterpoint challenged hackers to develop any web or mobile application that used the Clusterpoint Cloud as a back-end database solution. The winner -- <a href="http://rydrapp.co/?rydr=about" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Rydr</a> -- was awarded $10,000, and all team members received also Apple Watches as local winners of the AH series event in Silicon Valley! Clusterpoint chose this team because of the creativity and utility of the <a href="http://rydrapp.co/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Rydr API</a> that gives users access to on-demand car and taxi services data including price and time estimates, user account data, and driver data. Powered by the Clusterpoint Cloud, Rydr claims this app saves people time and money because users will always get the best deal when selecting an on-demand car or taxi.\r\n\r\nThe Rydr team used Clusterpoint as its analytics engine that collects useful data from the Rydr API giving them insight into how applications use their service. In the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K7SfsKmTcf0" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">demo</a>, a team member shows how the app can plot in real-time locations of drivers of on-demand car and taxi services. Another cool feature of the app is called Live Map. By clicking on a city name, the map gives the user updated locations of drivers of four ride-sharing companies – Uber, Lyft, Sidecar, and Flywheel – in a local area. Pretty cool! Live Map is just one small example of the useful data that can be collected and presented by combining the Clusterpoint database with the <a href="http://rydrapp.co/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Rydr API</a>. Read extended interview with Rydr team members <a href="http://angelhack.com/rydr-clusterpoint-a-match-made-in-hacker-heaven/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a>.\r\n<h2>Bitter</h2>\r\nOne of the runner-ups was a Bitter team – winners of Clusterpoint special prize at AH Manhattan event. This application, powered by the Clusterpoint database, is a geo-social-mobile application that allows users to share and explore the world around them – Tinder of Everything. This app builds a curated community of experiences and events by allowing users to up-vote or down-vote the world around them! When a user creates an event, their vote along with others get aggregated in Clusterpoint''s DBaaS cloud using the Node.js API library and are used to render the global map view that any user can check out. Each event is mapped to a marker on the global map so you can check out up-votes in your neighborhood or on a different continent!\r\n<h2>iHOPE</h2>\r\nDuring the Kochi event, iHOPE team developed an app to reduce food waste. This app provides a platform to donate, provide or share excess food from events like weddings, parties and more. The app is location-based and helps connect people who are donating food with charities that accept food donations for the needy.\r\n<h2>YamirukkaBayamen</h2>\r\nDuring the AngelHack in Chennai, the winners – YamirukkaBayamen – created the <a href="http://yamirukkabayamen.herokuapp.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">“Yaamiruka Bayamen”</a> app that addresses safety issues among people in their local society. With this app, users who are buying or moving into houses can choose safer locations using a safety index. The government can also increase police patrols in high-crime areas. The app was created using a Python script that scrapes news articles and stores the data in a Clusterpoint database. A Rails app consumes the data from the Clusterpoint database and paints the details on a Google map. What a great idea!\r\n\r\nThanks to all of you who used the Clusterpoint database during AngelHack!', 'Clusterpoint Winners from this Year’s AngelHack', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'clusterpoint-winners-from-this-years-angelhack', '', '', '2016-02-02 10:55:35', '2016-02-02 08:55:35', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?p=90', 7, 'post', '', 0),
(92, 1, '2015-11-20 13:41:17', '2015-11-20 11:41:17', 'With all the NoSQL database options available on the market today, including cloud-based Database-as- a-Service (DBaaS) options as well as installable software, you might wonder whether we need yet another DBaaS player – especially one with headquarters in as unlikely a place as Latvia.\r\n\r\nWell, get ready for Clusterpoint to surprise you. Clusterpoint offers a document-oriented DBaaS service that supports both JavaScript and XML. Fully ACID compliant. Instant scalability. And it has a home-built indexing engine that delivers blisteringly fast queries, even for complex, deeply structured JSON or XML documents.\r\n\r\nLatvia headquarters notwithstanding, their core team has serious tech cred, with years of experience working on the Google search engine. They bring that experience to the seriously difficult challenge of building a cloud-ready database engine that has the chops to compete with Amazon DynamoDB, MongoDB, and Cassandra, among others in an increasingly crowded field.\r\n\r\nIn fact, you can think of Clusterpoint as offering the best of each of these three offerings. The cloud-centric usability and pay-as-you-go business model of DynamoDB. The JavaScript support of MongoDB. And the broadly distributed, rapid scalability and transactionality of Cassandra.\r\n<h2>Indexing Implementation by Clusterpoint</h2>\r\nWith mature open source indexing and search technologies on the market like <a href="http://lucene.apache.org/index.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Apache Lucene</a> and its <a href="http://lucene.apache.org/solr/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Apache Solr</a> search server, you might wonder why Clusterpoint put the time and effort into building their own indexing engine. The answer lies in how they deal with hierarchical documents.\r\n\r\nDocument-oriented databases traditionally treat JSON and XML as document file types – essentially, long sequences of characters that might as well be plain text files. Indexing them, therefore, tends to be a brute force process that treats them as any other document format.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint’s indexing takes a smarter approach. It treats these documents as the hierarchical documents they are. Not only does this smart indexing deal well with large, deeply structured JSON and XML, it also enables the logical joining of such documents.\r\n\r\nWith earlier generation document databases, searching over multiple documents requires a concatenation of such documents, slowing down the searches and running into other capacity issues as the number and size of such documents grows. Clusterpoint, on the other hand, can treat a set of JSON files as a single indexed unit, even when one document appears as a node deep within another document.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint’s indexing scheme also supports more sophisticated querying of JSON and XML documents. In addition to a native query language, the latest version of Clusterpoint supports JS/SQL, a version of SQL specifically for querying such documents.\r\n\r\nThe best way to get a sense as to the power and ease-of-use of JS/SQL is via some examples. For example, with JS/SQL we can put JavaScript directly into SELECT/WHERE/ORDER BY clauses:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nfunction discount(category) {\r\n	discounts = {\r\n		"Books" : 0.1,\r\n		"Clothing" : 0.3,\r\n		"Home &amp; Garden" : 0.05,\r\n		"Sports" : 0.15\r\n	}\r\n	if (category in discounts) {\r\n		return discounts[category]\r\n	}\r\n	return 0;\r\n}\r\n\r\nSELECT name, price * (1.0 - discount(category)) AS discounted_price FROM product</code></pre>\r\nDevelopers can also place arbitrary JavaScript in GROUP BY clauses as well:\r\n<pre><code class="language-php">\r\nfunction PriceBucket(price) {\r\n	var boundaries = [0, 1, 5, 10, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000];\r\n	for (var i = 1; i &lt; boundaries.length; i++) {\r\n		if (price &gt;= boundaries[i - 1] &amp;&amp; price &lt; boundaries[i]) {\r\n			return boundaries[i - 1].toString() + " to " +\r\n				boundaries[i].toString();\r\n		}\r\n		return "above " +\r\n			boundaries[boundaries.length - 1].toString();\r\n	}\r\n}\r\nSELECT PriceBucket(price), COUNT() FROM product\r\nWHERE CONTAINS("mountain bike")\r\nGROUP BY PriceBucket(price);\r\n</code></pre>\r\nThe JavaScript above is straightforward for anyone who uses the language, and the SQL will be familiar to anyone with experience with traditional SQL.\r\n<h2>Comparing Clusterpoint to the Alternatives</h2>\r\nClusterpoint’s inherently distributed architecture provides instant (sub-second) scalability, similar perhaps to Cassandra clusters, but far faster than DynamoDB, hosted MongoDB, or other choices like IBM Cloudant or Microsoft DocumentDB.\r\n\r\nIts scalable ACID transactions are unusual in the world of NoSQL. Vendors like NuoDB offer ACID transactionality, and Cassandra offers tunable consistency. But DynamoDB, MongoDB, and most other NoSQL choices offer an eventual consistency-based transactional model.\r\n\r\nThe <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CAP_theorem" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">CAP theorem</a>, of course, states that no database management system can offer immediate consistency, partition tolerance, and high availability at the same time. In practice t his theorem means that if the nodes in a distributed database can’t communicate with each other, they can’t commit a transaction until such communication resumes.\r\n\r\nWith Cassandra’s tunable consistency, the admin can configure whether to allow commits when only some of the nodes are in communication with each other. A common setting is to allow commits with one more than half the nodes participating, known as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quorum_(distributed_computing)" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">quorum-based consistency</a>.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint takes a quorum-based approach, were most of the nodes must be able to communicate. But since Clusterpoint controls their own deployment environment (running in their own collocated data centers rather than AWS), the chances that such a quorum won’t be achievable is minuscule.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint’s support for XML as well as JSON differentiate it from most of the document databases on the market, and its sophisticated indexing and search capability enable full-text search, relevancy ranking, as well as 2D and 3D geospatial indexing and querying. MongoDB and Cloudant offer built-in indexing and search, while other options require a separate search add-on. Only Cloudant offers geospatial support as advanced as Clusterpoint.\r\n<h2>The Intellyx Take</h2>\r\nWhat’s it going to take for current DBaaS and NoSQL users to make the switch to Clusterpoint? The first step, of course, is trying it out. Good thing Clusterpoint gives away the first 10 Gigabytes of storage for free (for as long as you want), and the first 30 days are free, regardless of how much you use.\r\n\r\nAnd while DBaaS is clearly the wave of the future, Clusterpoint also offers an on-premise version as well, with no license fee and a simple install. So what are you waiting for?', 'Bespoke Indexing: An Important Database Differentiator', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bespoke-indexing-an-important-database-differentiator', '', '', '2016-02-02 11:20:46', '2016-02-02 09:20:46', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?p=92', 6, 'post', '', 0),
