(174, 1, '2015-10-19 16:22:16', '2015-10-19 13:22:16', 'Clusterpoint honoured as a leading European TMT company<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<b>BARCELONA and RIGA, LATVIA – 19 October 2015</b> - Clusterpoint, a database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS), announced today as Young Bull winner of the 2015 Bully Award, honouring outstanding European media and telecommunications (TMT) companies as presented by <a href="http://www.whitebull.com/">White Bull Summits</a>, champions of European innovation.\r\n\r\nA total of 60 European companies were named as finalists for the 2015 Bully Awards, selected from a pool of over 500 entries from the TMT sector. 30 deserving winners were selected by a panel of journalists and industry experts and announced at the 6th annual Pathways summit in Barcelona.\r\n\r\nThe winners fall into four categories:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b>Yearlings:</b> firms that seek or have received angel/seed rounds or equivalent; classic startups</li>\r\n	<li><b>Young Bulls:</b> firms that seek or have received Series A financing; early stage companies</li>\r\n	<li><b>Longhorns:</b> post Series A firms; growth stage companies</li>\r\n	<li><b>Minotaurs:</b> Hyper-Growth stage</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n“This year’s Bully Award applications were a clear indication that not just innovation but also endurance are alive and well in Europe,” said White Bull co-founder Elizabeth Perry. “Our judges were particularly impressed with the quality they saw this year in the Nordics, but saw a great cross section of firms from across the continent.”\r\n\r\n“We’re honoured to be named a 2015 Bully Award winner, and to be recognized as one of the leading TMT companies in Europe,” said Zigmars Rasscevskis, CEO of Clusterpoint. “It’s validating to be named a winner for this prestigious award, and we accept and share it with the entire Clusterpoint company and community.”\r\n\r\nEarlier this month <a href="http://www.clusterpoint.com/">Clusterpoint</a> launched Clusterpoint 4, an evolution of its database software into a “computing engine.” This unique platform combines an instantly scalable document-oriented database with computing so developers and businesses can process and analyze large amounts of data in real-time and at a reasonable cost. Furthermore, because Clusterpoint 4 was designed as a relational database replacement, they have built a new data manipulation and querying language in JS/SQL. This is critical because now JavaScript can be used for data retrieval and data transformation in a familiar SQL structure, making Clusterpoint 4 a computing engine that can not only store data, but process data and run arbitrary computations.\r\n\r\nThe White Bull judges carefully reviewed seed-stage, early-stage and growth-stage companies, and selected the winning companies they believe have demonstrated clear potential for further growth and a high probability for further success.\r\n\r\nWhite Bull has a successful track record in identifying Europe’s leading TMT companies, with over 75% of finalists receiving significant funding, expansion, or moving on to Exit.\r\n\r\nFor a complete list of the 2015 White Bull Bully Award winners, please visit <a href="http://whitebull.com/latest/meet-our-2015-bully-award-winners" rel="nofollow">http://whitebull.com/latest/meet-our-2015-bully-award-winners</a>\r\n<h2>About Clusterpoint</h2>\r\nClusterpoint is a database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS) for developers and small to medium size businesses worldwide that want instant scalability and massive distributed computing power for their growing database needs but without the hefty price tag. Founded in 2006, Clusterpoint has served business customers as an enterprise-oriented NoSQL database. Today the Clusterpoint database is used across different industries to drive 24/7 mission-critical web and mobile application solutions. For more information about our cloud-based service, visit <a href="http://www.clusterpoint.com/">www.clusterpoint.com</a>.\r\n<h2>About White Bull</h2>\r\nWhite Bull’s aim is not simply to produce events. White Bull is here to help companies succeed. Built upon the extensive knowledge and network of its founders and advisors, and in the spirit of the “wily beast” that lives inside all successful businesses, White Bull provides a platform that brings together the best and the brightest – Europe’s top technology and media leaders, entrepreneurs, innovators, investors, and visionaries. White Bull will respond to the needs and wants of the Technology, Media and Telecommunications (TMT) sector, while providing a forum for ongoing discussion. For more information, please visit White Bull at <a href="http://whitebull.com/" rel="nofollow">http://whitebull.com</a>, on <a href="http://www.facebook.com/whitebullsummits" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a> or follow White Bull on Twitter <a href="https://twitter.com/whitebullsummit" rel="nofollow">@whitebullsummit</a>.\r\n<h2>Media Contact:</h2>\r\nElizabeth Perry\r\nWhite Bull Summits\r\n<a href="tel:+34 93 802 1383">+34 93 802 1383</a>\r\n\r\nJohn Conrad\r\nClusterpoint\r\n<a href="tel:+1-703-390-1538">+1-703-390-1538</a>', 'Clusterpoint Wins Prestigious 2015 Bully Award', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'clusterpoint-wins-prestigious-2015-bully-award-clusterpoint-honoured-as-a-leading-european-tmt-company', '', '', '2016-02-25 16:24:08', '2016-02-25 14:24:08', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?post_type=press_releases&#038;p=174', 2, 'press_releases', '', 0),
(185, 1, '2016-03-03 13:15:55', '2016-03-03 11:15:55', '<p class="text">Maps have been very valuable to mankind since ancient times. At the beginning people had to look up to the sky and stars were their pointers. Then cartography brought us possibility to visit nearby places and sometimes even mystical parts of the world by looking at the maps. Nowadays maps are everywhere and we could not imagine our lives without some mapping solutions. We depend on maps when we drive, when we are traveling and looking for new and interesting places to stop by. Majority of maps are proprietary. We are limited in what we can do with them. And it’s more impossible than not to extract just portion of data. We need to use what we are given, even if it comes with user tracking and advertisements. Not everyone likes such lock in. That’s where crowdsourced, open data comes in. One of such data sets is OpenStreetMap (OSM).</p>\n<p class="text">Even though a lot of people think, that OSM is only a map, which is visible when you visit <a href="http://openstreetmap.org/" target="_blank">http://openstreetmap.org</a>, it''s actually much more than that. OSM is a big data set and particular map is just one of many representations of this data. One subset of OSM data is <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Points_of_interest" target="_blank">Points of interest</a> (POI). If you want to create some mapping services which would display POI data, you have several options:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Use <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Xapi" target="_blank">OSM Xapi</a>. This way you can access most up to date data. However this API is not suited for heavy usage. API tends to be slow and is rate limited.</li>\n	<li>You can download whole OSM data dump (called <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Planet.osm" target="_blank">planet.osm</a>) and process it with <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Osmosis">Osmosis</a>. That way you could extract data that you actually need, import it in your DB of choice and use it. This option will not be suited for most developers, because it requires extensive knowledge of the tools and very good hardware to handle big data dumps.</li>\n	<li>You can use service like MapQuest. Their <a href="https://developer.mapquest.com/products/spatial-search/" target="_blank">Search API</a> provides possibility to fetch POI data. However their free tier only allows 500 requests per day which might not be enough for you. You can either upgrade to paid plan or check out 4th option in our list.</li>\n	<li>You can use OSM POI db provided by <a href="http://clusterpoint.com/" target="_blank">Clusterpoint Cloud</a>. Yes, that''s right! We host extracted OpenStretMap Points of interest data and it''s available to anyone. We are covering all associated storage costs! Users are charged only for CPU power used to retrieve data. However thank''s to our generous <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/pricing" target="_blank">Free tier</a> you will be able to perform lots and lots of queries before coming close to Free CPU limit. Which means that OSM POI data queries for majority of you will be completely free of charge!</li>\n</ul>\nOSM POI data and Clusterpoint Cloud is a perfect match. By using our scalable infrastructure we can guarantee that your requests will always be handled very fast. Clusterpoint''s support for unstructured data documents, 2D &amp; 3D Geo-spatial indexing and Full-text search allows it''s users to create very feature rich applications. This tutorial is first in series about our public OSM POI database. You will learn about database structure and how to perform basic queries. In future tutorials we will go through more complex examples to explore different features and Clusterpoint server.\n<h2>Tutorial structure</h2>\n<p class="text">This tutorial is first in series about how to use OpenStreetMap POI data and different Geo related features of Clusterpoint server. We will learn about OSM POI db access, how to build search queries, how to search within shapes and how to do basic aggregations. In each section we will look at separate functions and classes. At the end we will put together everything we have learned and will assemble code needed for demo application.</p>\n\n<h2>OSM POI database</h2>\n<p class="text">To get access to OSM POI database you first need to <a href="https://cloud.clusterpoint.com/#authentication/signup" target="_blank">sign up</a> for Clusterpoint Cloud account. It’s free of charge. After sign in click on Public databases.</p>\n<p class="text"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-188" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ccloud_1.png" alt="ccloud_1" width="798" height="102" /></p>\n<p class="text">then on pulic::osm_poi</p>\n<p class="text"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-187" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ccloud_2.png" alt="ccloud_2" width="807" height="213" /></p>\n<p class="text">To actually browse around data click on Query button. This will open query window with first 20 objects.</p>\n<p class="text"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-186" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ccloud_3.png" alt="ccloud_3" width="797" height="189" /></p>\n<p class="text">There are many fields in each document. However in this tutorial we will be taking closer look at just a few of them.</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>id</strong> - this is object''s ID. It corresponds to real OSM object ID. You can confirm that by opening URL <code>http://api.openstreetmap.org/api/0.6/[type]/[id]</code> in your Web browser. Replace [id] with value from id field and [type] with value from type field.</li>\n	<li><strong>lat</strong> - object''s Latitude</li>\n	<li><strong>lon</strong> - object''s Longitude</li>\n	<li><strong>tags</strong> - object''s <a href="http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Tags" target="_blank">tags </a>. Tags are very useful as they give meaning to the data. They describe what particular object really represents. Each object can have many tags. Even though there are guidelines on how to set up tags, there are no strict rules about that. As a result it''s not uncommon that some objects are missing very valuable tags. Some similar objects are described with different tags etc. Because of that it''s sometimes complex to filter and group such data. However relative freedom in tags is what makes OSM data so unique and valuable.</li>\n</ul>\n<p class="text">If you are using OSM POI data in your projects, make sure to put correct copyright notice wherever you display data:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n© &lt;a href="http://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright" target="_blank"&gt;OpenStreetMap contributors&lt;/a&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<h2>OSM POI access from API</h2>\n<p class="text">To access OSM POI data from scripts we will be using Clusterpoint’s <a href="https://github.com/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">PHP client library</a>. There are libraries for <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/docs/?page=API_Library_Downloads" target="_blank">other languages too</a>. Consult documentation about how to download and set up one that’s suited for your environment. It should be easy to translate PHP examples to other languages. However if you run into problems, you can always refer to <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/docs/?page=Reference">Reference</a> where it’s shown how to do the same thing in various languages.</p>\n<p class="text">You can download <a href="https://github.com/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">PHP Client from Github</a> or you can use <a href="http://getcomposer.org/" target="_blank">Composer</a>. In case of Composer you will need to require clusterpoint/php-client-api from <a href="https://packagist.org/packages/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">Packagist</a>. Keep in mind that default version for download (at the moment of writing) is 3.0 which is a bit outdated. To get most up to date version require "dev-master".</p>\n<p class="text">To access public::osm_poi database from PHP we need to create a connection</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$cps_connection = new CPS_Connection(\n                            new CPS_LoadBalancer([\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-0.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-1.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-2.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\n                                    ''tcps://cloud-eu-3.clusterpoint.com:9008'',\n                                ]),\n                            ''public::osm_poi'',\n                            ''USERNAME'',\n                            ''PASSWORD'',\n                            ''document'', ''//document/id'',\n                            [''account'' =&gt; ''ACCOUNT_ID'']\n    );\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">Replace USERNAME with your username, PASSWORD with your password and ACCOUNT_ID with your account id. Even though it’s possible to use the same username and password which you use to log into Clusterpoint Cloud UI panel, we strongly recommend to create separate user with access to only this database. Consult <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/docs/?page=Authorisation" target="_blank">documentation</a> on how to create a new user.</p>\n<p class="text">In LoadBalancer I have specified connection through SSL. That’s the recommended type of connection. However if for some reason you can not use SSL replace <i>tcps</i> with <i>tcp</i> and change port from <i>9008</i> to <i>9007</i>.</p>\n\n<h2>Shape definitions</h2>\n<p class="text">In Clusterpoint it’s very easy to use search within shapes. There are two supported types of shapes: polygons and circles. It’s possible to use several shapes in one request. By combining shapes you can support very complex Geo queries. This time we will look only on how to search within a circle. In next tutorial we will go through various shape combinations (separate shapes, intersecting ones etc.).</p>\n<p class="text">All queries involving shapes should consist of two parts: shape definition and usage of said shape. To define circle in PHP use CPS_CircleDefinition:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$circle = CPS_CircleDefinition(''circle'', [$lat, $lng], ''1 km'', ''lat'', ''lon'');\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">In first parameter you should pass identificator for particular circle. I used "circle", but it could have been "bigcircle" or anything else. Second is array of latitude and longitude. Third is radius of the circle. To set radius in miles use <i>mi</i> instead of <i>km</i>. Last two parameters are names of latitude and longitude fields in db.</p>\n<p class="text">Once circle is defined we can use it in search query.</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$query = CPS_Term('' &gt;&lt;circle'');\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">This query tells server to look for objects which are inside of circle. <code>&lt;&gt;</code> would tell to look outside of circle. Notice that you should leave one empty space before <code>&lt;&gt;</code> and <code>&gt;&lt;</code> operators. If we would have used "bigcircle" in first parameter for circle definition, then search query would be <code>&gt;&lt;bigcircle</code>.</p>\n<p class="text">When we will create search request we will need to use previously defined <code>$circle</code> to add circle definition to search request (you will see that further in tutorial).\n<strong>Tip:</strong> if there are some shapes which you use very often and do not want to send shape definitions with each request you can define shapes in database configuration. However that’s not possible with public::osm_poi database. But know that such option is available if you ever need that in your other databases.</p>\n\n<h2>Search within tags</h2>\n<p class="text">One of useful OSM POI tags is <i>amenity</i>. It can be used to group and filter objects by their type. For example, if you want to look for Cafes, you can use</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$query = CPS_Term(''cafe'', ''tags/amenity'');\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">if you want to find any object which have amenity cafe or bar:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$query = CPS_Term(''{ cafe bar }'', ''tags/amenity'');\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">In case of OSM POI we know that values of tags do not have empty spaces. If there were values with empty spaces in them, you would need to use double quotes (ASCII 34) to contain phrase. Example:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$query = CPS_Term(''{ cafe "fast food" bar } '', ''tags/amenity'');\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">One last thing. Not all objects have amenity tag. That’s why you might want to search objects for which amenity tag does not exist. To do that you need to use "does not exist" operator:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$query = CPS_Term(''=""'', ''tags/amenity'');\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">Of course you can combine <code class="php">=""</code> with other values. This example will search for objects which have amenity tag equal to cafe or amenity tag is not set up at all.</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$query = CPS_Term(''{ ="" cafe }'', ''tags/amenity'');\n</code></pre>\n<h2>Aggregation</h2>\n<p class="text">Clusterpoint server allows to perform different types of aggregations. In this tutorial we will perform only one simple aggregation. More complex examples will be demonstrated in future tutorials. We again return to amenity tag. To show amenities filter in our application we need to get distinct <i>tags/amenity</i> values. Aggregation query for that is straight forward:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$aggregate = ''DISTINCT tags.amenity'';\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">It is possible to send several aggregations within one request. That saves script-server roundtrips.</p>\n\n<h2>Search request</h2>\n<p class="text">We have now learned how to write search query and how to write aggregation query. But those queries alone can’t do much. We need to send them to the Clusterpoint Cloud. To do that CPS_SearchRequest should be used:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$query = CPS_Term(''hotel''); // search in whole document for hotel\n$query .= CPS_Term('' &gt;&lt;circle''); // search within circle\n$offset = 0;\n$docs = 50;\n$search_request = new CPS_SearchRequest($query, $offset, $docs);\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">First parameter is search query. Second is offset, but third is how many documents to return. This query will look within circle for objects that in any tag have value "hotel" in them. Query will return first 50 objects.\nWhen search request is instantiated we can do a bit more setup. First thing is to tell which fields we want to be returned. We want whole documents, that’s why</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$search_request-&gt;setParam(''list'', ''&lt;document&gt;yes&lt;/document&gt;'');\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">should be used. Circle was used in the query. Because of that circle definitions should be added to the request:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$search_request-&gt;setShape($circle);\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">It is possible to set up aggregation in the same request:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$search_request-&gt;setAggregate($aggregate);\n</code></pre>\n<h2>Response</h2>\n<p class="text">Once search request is constructed we can send search request to the server and in return we can get response with objects that matched search query. As well as aggregation result.</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$search_response = $cps_connection-&gt;sendRequest($search_request);</code></pre>\n<p class="text">Response objects have several useful helpers:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li><code class="php">$search_response-&gt;getHits()</code> - count of matched objects</li>\n	<li><code class="php">$search_response-&gt;getFrom()</code> - offset that was used in search query</li>\n	<li><code class="php">$search_response-&gt;getTo()</code> - number of last element</li>\n</ul>\n<p class="text">To get actual matched documents use getDocuments:</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\nforeach ($search_response-&gt;getDocuments() as $id =&gt; $document) {\n// perform some actions with documents\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">By default documents are returned as SimpleXML. To override that you can pass constant:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>DOC_TYPE_ARRAY</strong> - to get array</li>\n	<li><strong>DOC_TYPE_STDCLASS</strong> - to get std class</li>\n	<li><strong>DOC_TYPE_SIMPLEXML</strong> - to get simplexml</li>\n</ul>\n<p class="text">To get data from aggregation you need to use <code>getAggregate()</code></p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$aggregated_data = $search_response-&gt;getAggregate(DOC_TYPE_ARRAY);\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">In this example aggregation data will be returned as array. As it’s possible to send several aggregation queries in one request <code>$aggregated_data</code> will hold response from all aggregations. At index 0 you will get data for first aggregation, at index 1 for second etc.</p>\n\n<h2>Demo application</h2>\n<p class="text">Let’s put together everything we have learned today and build fully functional application. This demo application will allow to look up objects in specific section of the map, will allow to find objects by search phrase and filter objects by Amenity tag. By click on map marker it will be possible to view all tags of particular object.</p>\n<p class="text">For demo application I have used few very useful tools:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>UI is built by using CSS from <a href="http://getbootstrap.com/" target="_blank">Bootstrap</a> framework. On JS part <a href="https://jquery.com/" target="_blank">jQuery</a> was used. Both of them are very well known among developers and are de-facto standards.</li>\n	<li>On server side Clusterpoint <a href="https://github.com/clusterpoint/php-client-api" target="_blank">PHP Client</a> is used. As well as <a href="http://www.slimframework.com/" target="_blank">Slim framework</a>.</li>\n	<li>For mapping solution Google Maps API was chosen. It’s very common to see OSM POI data on maps generated from OSM data. However that’s not some sort of requirement. It’s perfectly valid to use Google Maps in combination with OSM POI data. Keep in mind that if you are using mapping solution which is not built from OSM data, you might run into situation when POI object is shown in the middle of the street or not near a street at all (it''s possible that OSM have roads which are not depicted on Google Maps).</li>\n</ul>\n<p class="text">Do no worry if you are not familiar with some of used tools. If you have basic programming knowledge, you should be able to follow through.</p>\n<p class="text">You can access source code of demo app at <a href="https://github.com/Endijs/osm-poi-clusterpoint-cloud-demo-part1" target="_blank">https://github.com/Endijs/osm-poi-clusterpoint-cloud-demo-part1</a> and you can view live application demo at <a href="http://osmpoi.endijs.com/" target="_blank">http://osmpoi.endijs.com</a>. If you want to set up application on your own server follow Installation notes in <code>readme.md</code> file.</p>\n<p class="text">This demo application have only 1 file which handles all communication with Clusterpoint Cloud. Let’s take a look at it ( /public/index.php ) and discuss main parts of it.\nAt the beginning we require Composer’s autoload file and some configuration files.</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\nrequire_once ''../vendor/autoload.php'';\nrequire_once ''../cfg/cps.php'';\nrequire_once ''../cfg/google.php'';\n</code></pre>\n<p class="text">Slim framework application gets instantiated</p>\n\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$app = new \\Slim\\Slim([\n        ''debug''          =&gt; false,\n        ''templates.path'' =&gt; ''../templates'',\n        ''cps''            =&gt; $cps_config,\n        ''google''         =&gt; $google_config,\n    ]\n);\n</code></pre>\nRoute to index page. Configuration about Google Maps API is retrieved and Maps API key gets assigned to the view. And then template gets rendered.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$app-&gt;get(''/'', function() use ($app) {\n    $google_config = $app-&gt;config(''google'');\n    $app-&gt;view-&gt;setData(''maps_api_key'', $google_config[''maps_api_key'']);\n    $app-&gt;render(''index.php'');\n});\n</code></pre>\nThis route handles all Ajax requests from applications UI.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$app-&gt;get("/api/list/:lat/:lng/:radius/*", function ($lat, $lng, $radius) use ($app) {\n}\n</code></pre>\nCast data types for mandatory fields and retrieve optional request values.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$lat = (float)$lat;\n$lng = (float)$lng;\n$radius = (int)$radius;\n$q = trim((string)$app-&gt;request-&gt;get(''q'', '''')); // search phrase\n$amenities = (array)$app-&gt;request-&gt;get(''amenities'', []); // amenities filter\n$page = (int)$app-&gt;request-&gt;get(''page'', 1); // page\n</code></pre>\nBasic validation. In real application you should validate all input from user.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\nif ($page &lt; 1) {\n    $page = 1;\n}\n</code></pre>\nData will be returned in this structure.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$objects = [\n        ''total'' =&gt; 0,\n        ''from'' =&gt; 0,\n        ''to'' =&gt; 0,\n        ''pages'' =&gt; 0,\n        ''current_page'' =&gt; 0,\n        ''list''  =&gt; [],\n        ''amenities'' =&gt; [],\n];\n</code></pre>\nConnection to Clusterpoint Cloud gets instantiated.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$cps_connection = new CPS_Connection(\n                            new CPS_LoadBalancer($config[''connection'']),\n                            $config[''database''],\n                            $config[''username''],\n                            $config[''password''],\n                            ''document'', ''//document/id'',\n                            [''account'' =&gt; $config[''account'']]\n);\n$docs = 50;\n$offset = $docs * ($page - 1);\n</code></pre>\nRadius is received in meters. But Clusterpoint expects values to be in km.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$radius = $radius / 1000;\n</code></pre>\nShape (circle) definition. This will need to be attached to search query.\n<pre><code class="language-php">\n$circle = CPS_CircleDefinition(''circle'', [$lat, $lng], $radius . '' km'', ''lat'', ''lon'');\n</code></pre>\nFirst rule in search query. We are interested in objects within circle.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Easy OpenStreetMap POI maps with Clusterpoint Cloud', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '27-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-03-03 13:15:55', '2016-03-03 11:15:55', '', 27, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/27-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `cp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(167, 1, '2016-02-25 11:49:03', '2016-02-25 09:49:03', 'Problem Statement: In a classic corporate environment, a data warehouse stores data extracted from operational databases and external data sources. It is mostly used for analysis and for reporting on historical data for specific business needs, usually in conjunction with visual business intelligence (BI) tools. The data is loaded into the data warehouse from the operational database or other data sources regularly via a batch ETL process or in some cases, in real-time.\n\n<!--more-->\n<h2>Alternative Solutions</h2>\n<u>Relational (SQL) Database and Star Schema</u>\n\nA typical approach to creating a data warehouse is to use a relational database with a star schema. In a star schema there are two types of tables used:\n<ul>\n	<li>FACT tables, which record measures about particular events or states, such as a customer ordering a particular product, usage of a particular service, a customer contacting the help desk, a sensor reading etc.</li>\n	<li>DIMENSION tables, describe what a particular item in the FACT table may be related to, such as customer, product, or the date and location an event occurred</li>\n</ul>\nFACT tables contain measurements as well as references to DIMENSION tables. Thus, the data model is normalized, but the overall complexity of the structure is still relatively low\n\n<img class="aligncenter wp-image-156" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Screen-Shot-2016-02-15-at-13.31.16.png" alt="Screen Shot 2016-02-15 at 13.31.16" width="445" height="313" />\n\nThe star schema (see Figure 1) allows aggregation queries to be formulated and executed, such as counting or summing a particular measure and slicing it along a particular set of dimensions. For example, a typical analytical query could involve computing net sales of a particular product and slicing it by region.\n\nPain points of this relational (SQL) solution include:\n<ul>\n	<li>Due to architectural constraints, relational databases experience scaling limitations. These limitations often result in a loss of performance and complex queries cannot be executed in sub- second time, resulting in a setup where reports can only be generated on a daily basis.</li>\n	<li>Relational databases do not support extended, unstructured data formats, such as text documents or hierarchical and repeated structured objects (for example, JSON objects).</li>\n</ul>\n<u>NoSQL Technology</u>\n\nWith their easily-distributed architectures, NoSQL technologies are well-suited to solving scalability issues by scaling horizontally. There are two possible NoSQL solutions to the scalability problem, either a more traditional NoSQL database, or a MapReduce-based compute cluster. In the case of MapReduce, for example with Hadoop, one often runs SQL-like queries with technology like Apache Hive.\n\nThe main pain point here is the data model. Typical NoSQL technologies would require further denormalization of the star schema handled by relational databases. This would result in significant expansion of the data.\n<h2>Clusterpoint Data Warehouse Solution</h2>\nClusterpoint is a SuperSQL database, which means it is a super-set of SQL functionally. It supports joins and ACID-compliant transactions and can effectively reference data from one table into another. Along with that, it has important NoSQL characteristics in terms of horizontal scalability and handling of unstructured data and hierarchical data models.\n\nThus, for a data warehouse our proposal is to build a hybrid model where FACT tables are sharded (distributed among computational nodes) and DIMENSION tables are replicated among computational nodes. This model allows Clusterpoint to do effective parallelization of computation and join data from FACT and DIMENSION tables efficiently (see Figure 2).\n<img class="wp-image-168 size-full aligncenter" src="https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/figure_2.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="auto" />\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Example Deployments</h2>\nImagine a setup where each computational node holds 1 billion FACT records and few million DIMENSION records.\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n<td>On Single Machine</td>\n<td>10 Server Cluster</td>\n<td> 30 Server Cluster</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of FACT records</td>\n<td> 1000000000</td>\n<td> 10000000000</td>\n<td> 30000000000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of DIMENSION records</td>\n<td> 10000000</td>\n<td> 100000000</td>\n<td> 300000000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> FACT records per CPU core</td>\n<td> 83333333</td>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Bytes per record</td>\n<td> 2000</td>\n<td> 2000</td>\n<td> 2000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Raw data size (on HDD), TB</td>\n<td> 2,02</td>\n<td> 20,2</td>\n<td> 60,6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Bytes in indexes</td>\n<td> 200</td>\n<td> 200</td>\n<td> 200</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Index size (on SSD), TB</td>\n<td>0,202</td>\n<td> 2,02</td>\n<td> 6,06</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\nSpecification of a machine in cluster.\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Processor</td>\n<td>2 x 6-core</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>HDD</td>\n<td>2 TB HDD</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>SSD</td>\n<td> 2 x 256GB SSD</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>RAM</td>\n<td> 128 GB</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>Indexing Schemes</h2>\nAs the most efficient indexing scheme, Clusterpoint employs directly addressable value array indexes. In Clusterpoint, every document version, when inserted or replacing an existing document with the same primary key, gets a local document id assigned. Local doc ids are simply a sequence of increasing integers. Thus, a directly addressable index is an array of values addressed by a doc id. This scheme makes Clusterpoint query execution extremely fast, as it is optimized for index access from RAM and SSDs.\n\nDirectly addressable value array indexes are created for values that are used in aggregation functions, filtering, or joins between FACT and DIMENSION tables.\n\nFinally, the raw data itself is stored on an HDD, which is an inexpensive storage media. Raw data is not used in aggregation queries executed in typical data warehouse workloads. Raw records are instead used for persistence, recovery and replication during single machine failures in the cluster and for creation of indexes upon schema changes.\n<h2>Example Queries</h2>\nThe execution times are based on example deployment describes in the previous section.\n\nA typical data warehouse workload is comprised mostly of analytical queries that aggregate over a large number of FACT records and filter or categorize them based on values in DIMENSION tables.\n\nAs an example consider the following tables:\nD_CUSTOMER - a table containing customer information\nD_PRODUCT - a table containing product information\nF_MEASURE - a fact table recording customer specific measures, such as purchases, inquiries or product related usage statistics\n<h2>Broad Aggregation</h2>\nIn a broad aggregation, we aggregate over all (or a large proportion) of the records in the FACT table.\n\nAn example query might look like this:\n\nSELECT SUM(F_MEASURE.AMOUNT_CHARGED), D_PRODUCT.NAME\nFROM F_MEASURE INNER JOIN D_PRODUCT ON F_MEASURE.ID_PRODUCT = D_PRODUCT.ID\nGROUP BY D_PRODUCT.NAME\n\nQuery analysis.\n\nIn this case, Clusterpoint processes every record in the FACT table. There are two operations it performs: first it does an inner join with the D_PRODUCT table and then it aggregates values. A common approach of relational databases is to use a hash join in this situation. Clusterpoint, however, takes advantage of its directly addressable array index. It stores the foreign key of D_PRODUCT table as its local doc id, which is used as the array index. Thus for Clusterpoint, joining the tables is as cheap as single main memory address dereferencing. As such, Clusterpoint can process up to 20 million records per CPU core per second.\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements</td>\n<td>10000000000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements per core</td>\n<td>83333333</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CPU-core time per element, sec</td>\n<td>0,05</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Query execution time, sec</td>\n<td>4,167</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Narrowly Constrained Aggregation</span>\n\nIn this type of query, we aggregate over a constrained set of records. An example FACT record set serving as input for aggregation is on the order of hundreds of thousands of records.\n\nAn example query might look like this:\nSELECT SUM(F_MEASURE.AMOUNT_CHARGED), D_CUSTOMER.CUSTOMER_SEGMENT\nFROM F_MEASURE INNER JOIN D_CUSTOMER ON F_MEASURE.ID_CUSTOMER = D_CUSTOMER.ID\nWHERE F_MEASURE.SERVICE_START = ‘True’\nGROUP BY D_CUSTOMER.CUSTOMER_SEGMENT\n<div class="page" title="Page 6">\n<div class="section">\n<div class="layoutArea">\n<div class="column">\n\nQuery analysis.\n\nIn this case, Clusterpoint performs an exact match on an index created on the SERVICE_START field. The exact match index contains a list of local doc ids that match the criteria, thus Clusterpoint spends computational cycles only on records contributing to the result set. The query execution time spent on processing items is negligible, so the total query time is dominated by the network overhead of communication from client to processing nodes and back.\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements</td>\n<td>100000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements per core</td>\n<td>833</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CPU-core time per element, sec</td>\n<td>0,05</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Query execution time, sec</td>\n<td>0,000042</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Narrowly Constrained Aggregation with Join</span>\n\nIn this case we also aggregate over a constrained set of records, again on the order of hundreds of thousands. Unlike the previous case, the constraint is put on the joined DIMENSION table instead of the FACT table.\n\nAn example query might look like this:\n\nSELECT SUM(F_MEASURE.AMOUNT_CHARGED), D_CUSTOMER.CUSTOMER_SEGMENT\nFROM F_MEASURE INNER JOIN D_CUSTOMER ON F_MEASURE.ID_CUSTOMER = D_CUSTOMER.ID\nWHERE D_CUSTOMER.AGE = 35\nGROUP BY D_CUSTOMER.CUSTOMER_SEGMENT\n\nQuery analysis.\n\nIn this case, Clusterpoint has to do the join between the two tables even though the resulting set is small. Clusterpoint filters the entire FACT table against the hash set of IDs from the dimensions table that match the query parameters. The lookup against the hash set is relatively inexpensive, and we can process up to 80 million records per second.\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements</td>\n<td>10000000000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements per core</td>\n<td>83333333</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CPU-core time per element, sec</td>\n<td>0,0125</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Query execution time, sec</td>\n<td>1,041667</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Computational Queries</span>\n\nHere, instead of standard SQL we execute a JS/SQL query that does custom JavaScript calculation on each record.\n\nAn example query, which counts number of customer actions in a geographical grid might look like this:\n\nfunction grid_cell(x, y) {\nreturn Math.floor((x - x0) / x_step) + “ “ + Math.floor((y - y0) / y_step);\n}\n\nSELECT grid_cell(D_CUSTOMER.GPS_X, D_CUSTOMER_.GPS_Y) AS cell, COUNT(*)\nFROM F_MEASURE INNER JOIN D_CUSTOMER ON F_MEASURE.ID_CUSTOMER = D_CUSTOMER.ID\nWHERE F_MEASURE.DATE = ‘$today’\nGROUP BY cell\n\nQuery Analysis.\n\nFor this type of query, the Clusterpoint query optimizer cannot use indexes directly to find the constrained records set or group key for aggregation. The V8 JavaScript engine is invoked on each record, and we are able to process 500,000 records per second per CPU core. However, the query also constrains the set of records to just a single day’s worth, cutting down the search space.\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements</td>\n<td>20000000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Number of elements per core</td>\n<td>166667</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CPU-core time per element, sec</td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Query execution time, sec</td>\n<td>0,333</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>Extended Use Cases</h2>\nThe query examples above represent classical data warehouse workloads. However, Clusterpoint’s extensible data model also allows for advanced computational capabilities.\n<h3>Unstructured Data - Text Search &amp; Analysis</h3>\nWhen using Clusterpoint as data warehouse platform, it is possible to mix textual/unstructured data with tabular/structured data. For example some DIMENSIONs might contain textual information such as textual descriptions of the products or legal documents associated with the sales events captured in the FACT tables. This allows to analyse events connected with products identified with advanced text retrieval or analysis.\n<h3>Geospatial</h3>\nClusterpoint is excellent at handling geospatial data, because it builds two-dimensional indexes and provides built-in functions to locate objects within specific geographic shapes and use distance based calculations. Extrapolation &amp; Predictive Analytics Clusterpoint extends SQL query language with JavaScript scripting capabilities. This allows arbitrary complex computations including predictive or regression models run right in the the database and next to the data. It is easy to create queries not only for historic data, but augment it with forecasts and evaluate different what-if scenarios. Conclusion Clusterpoint technology, together with a data model which distributes FACT tables among computational nodes and hyper-replicates dimension tables, allows effective real-time processing of data warehouse workloads for deployments handling up to a billion items per computational node of commodity hardware.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>', 'Real-Time Data Warehouse', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '155-autosave-v1', '', '', '2016-02-25 11:49:03', '2016-02-25 09:49:03', '', 155, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/155-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(168, 1, '2016-02-25 11:23:53', '2016-02-25 09:23:53', '', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'figure_2', '', '', '2016-02-25 11:24:08', '2016-02-25 09:24:08', '', 155, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/figure_2.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(171, 1, '2015-06-16 08:00:22', '2015-06-16 05:00:22', 'Clusterpoint Brings Instantly Scalable and Massively Distributed Computing Power in the Form of Cloud-Based Databases to the Masses, With a Disruptive Pricing Model<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<b>RIGA, LATVIA - Clusterpoint</b>, a NoSQL database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS), today announced that it is launching Clusterpoint 3.0 in North America and opening a new server cluster in Dallas, TX, as the Latvian-based company seeks to expand its innovative technology to developers and small to medium sized businesses (SMBs) in North America, a market that craves instant scalability and massive distributed computing power for their growing database needs but without the hefty price tag.\r\n\r\nAs world data volumes continue to grow, data management has become absolutely critical. Today businesses and organizations need to process and analyze large amounts of data in real-time to be able to make effective decisions. To address this need, the company created Clusterpoint 3.0, a cloud-based NoSQL database that allows developers to scale instantly regardless of the data volume.\r\n\r\n"Our mission is to accelerate computing and the database plays a very central role in computing infrastructure today," says Zigmars Raascevskis, CEO of Clusterpoint. "Developers who are maintaining their own databases face two major obstacles because of hardware: fixed capacity and speed limitations. This is why we have built a cloud-based database service. In the cloud the developer''s database request can be distributed among hundreds of servers in parallel, significantly reducing clock time to get a result."\r\n\r\nIn addition to delivering instant scalability and massive distributed computing power in the form of a cloud-based database, developers benefit from a truly unique pricing model that is appealing to individual developers and those at SMBs. Clusterpoint 3.0 offers a true pay-per-use model, disrupting the tiered pricing model of today''s traditional DBAAS offerings. No other DBAAS company charges in this manner.\r\n\r\nIn traditional database pricing models, developers who own or rent hardware must provision a specific number of servers and capacity. This can be difficult because hardware and capacity requirements can change quickly. Furthermore, developers can be penalized for going beyond what they provisioned and possibly suffer from related performance issues. Conversely, developers may be subject to paying for capacity that is never used. With Clusterpoint''s cloud-based database, resources are allocated upon need and accounted per request on millisecond granularity. The resulting cost benefit can be 3X or even 10X, compared with traditional pricing models, and absolutely no hardware provisioning is required.\r\n\r\nMailigen, a leading web-based integrated marketing software provider, uses Clusterpoint 3.0 DBAAS to support its customers who need the ability to power their email marketing campaigns at a moment''s notice. "We have customers with large and small client databases sending millions of emails per day. They need to know that we can support whatever they need instantly and without the hefty price tag that comes with maintaining large amounts of data. The instant scalability and massive distributed computing power that the Clusterpoint 3.0 provides enables us to offer a valuable service to our customers at an attractive price," said CEO and Founder, Janis Rozenblats, Mailigen.\r\n\r\n<strong>Dallas Server Cluster</strong>\r\n\r\nAs part of launching Clusterpoint 3.0 in the U.S. market, Clusterpoint is announcing the opening of its first server facility in Dallas, TX. The facility is located strategically in the middle of the country to best serve customers in North America.\r\nThis facility is Clusterpoint''s first major investment in the U.S. and demonstrates its commitment to the marketplace. With this facility, Clusterpoint currently operates two server clusters worldwide. The other facility is located in Europe.\r\n<h2>About Clusterpoint</h2>\r\nClusterpoint is a NoSQL database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS) for developers and small to medium size businesses worldwide that want instant scalability and massive distributed computing power for their growing database needs but without the hefty price tag. Founded in 2006, Clusterpoint has served business customers as an enterprise-oriented NoSQL database. Today the Clusterpoint database is used across different industries to drive 24/7 mission-critical web and mobile application solutions. For more information about our cloud-based service, visit www.clusterpoint.com.\r\n<h2>Contact Information</h2>\r\nJohn Conrad\r\n<a href="mailto:conrad@merrittgrp.com">conrad@merrittgrp.com\r\n</a>703-390-1538', 'Clusterpoint Launches Cloud-Based Database-As-A-Service Offering and New Server Cluster in the U.S.', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'clusterpoint-launches-cloud-based-database-as-a-service-offering-and-new-server-cluster-in-the-u-s', '', '', '2016-02-25 16:15:45', '2016-02-25 14:15:45', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?post_type=press_releases&#038;p=171', 5, 'press_releases', '', 0),
(172, 1, '2015-06-17 16:16:12', '2015-06-17 13:16:12', 'The new Telia Latvija service will allow growing business to process large data sets in the cloud.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<b>RIGA, LATVIA — Clusterpoint</b>, a NoSQL database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS), announced today a strategic partnership agreement with Telia Latvija, one of the leading telecommunication service providers in Latvia. In the course of this partnership, Clusterpoint will augment Telia Latvija’s cloud computing services with Clusterpoint’s DBaaS stack, running on existing partners’ infrastructure, to create a competitive alternative in the database market.\r\n\r\nThe partnership offers current customers the opportunity to keep their infrastructure in one cloud, use our readily available DBaaS, avoid setup and management, and pay only for what they use in terms of data. In addition, the partnership means users won’t have to be concerned with hardware provisioning or adding another supplier.\r\n\r\nAccording to recent studies, analysts predict that in the coming years, most of growth in computing will be spent on the cloud as opposed to on-premise. Additionally, the percentage of U.S. small businesses using cloud computing is expected to more than double during the next six years, from 37 percent to nearly 80 percent, according to a study from consulting firm Emergent Research and financial software company Intuit.\r\n\r\nThe current cloud computing industry, led by the “Big 4” – Amazon (AWS), Microsoft (Azure), Google (Cloud) and IBM (BlueMix) - have been pushing proprietary DBAAS as an alternative to installing a database stack for every customer. This shared and optimized DBAAS creates massive utility for the customers, because each of them does not have to maintain and manage their own database deployment and common system for performance advantages.\r\n\r\n“Information scalability is a must,” said Zigmars Rasscevskis, CEO of Clusterpoint. “Studies have shown that in a few years most of the data in the world will be managed by document-oriented databases. High-performance, ACID-compliant transactions are key to enabling technology for this transition. And now, by joining forces with Telia Latvija, we truly believe we are able to challenge industry standards and offer a competitive alternative to our future and current customer base.”\r\n\r\nThe choice to partner with Telia was not only due to the fact that they are closely aligned with Clusterpoint’s current customer corporate infrastructure, but because of their understanding of the needs of enterprise clients. Through this partnership, Clusterpoint and Telia will be able to cross sell and develop new products and services for future and existing IT infrastructure clients, where cloud computing is offered in a broader package.\r\n\r\n“Today, most cloud computing vendors provide bare metal or visualized servers - the bread and butter of cloud computing - but this offering becomes commoditized since there are comparable computing resources out there,” said Mikus Ozols, CEO of Telia Latvija. “We decided that this was the right time to partner with Clusterpoint and bring on a value-add to our future product development. By augmenting Telia’s cloud computing service ‘Cloudy’ with Clusterpoint’s DBaaS stack, we’re now able to offer customers an instantly scalable database as a service solution - a competitive product we’re proud to deliver.”\r\n<h2>About Clusterpoint</h2>\r\nClusterpoint is a NoSQL database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS) for developers and small to medium size businesses worldwide that want instant scalability and massive distributed computing power for their growing database needs but without the hefty price tag. Founded in 2006, Clusterpoint has served business customers as an enterprise-oriented NoSQL database. Today the Clusterpoint database is used across different industries to drive 24/7 mission-critical web and mobile application solutions. For more information about our cloud-based service, visit www.clusterpoint.com.\r\n<h2>About Telia Latvija</h2>\r\nTelia Latvija was founded in 1992 and it is currently 100% part of the TeliaSonera AB group.\r\nTelia Latvija is one of the leading telecommunication service providers in Latvia having implemented internet and data transmission solutions throughout the all Latvian territory. By enlarging the range of services, Telia Latvija has built one of the most modern data centres in the Baltics, as well as is the first in the Baltic region begin to offer the latest generation cloud computing services based on this and other Telia Latvija data centres.\r\n<h2>Additional information:</h2>\r\nPeteris Janovskis, Director, Business Development\r\ncell: +371 29 229 885, e-mail: <a href="mailto:peteris@clusterpoint.com">peteris@clusterpoint.com</a>', 'Clusterpoint Signs Partnership Agreement with Telia Latvija to Provide Database as a Service', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'clusterpoint-signs-partnership-agreement-with-telia-latvija-to-provide-database-as-a-service', '', '', '2016-02-25 16:18:47', '2016-02-25 14:18:47', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?post_type=press_releases&#038;p=172', 4, 'press_releases', '', 0),
(173, 1, '2015-10-08 16:19:27', '2015-10-08 13:19:27', 'Unlike other NoSQL databases available today, Clusterpoint 4 supports ACID-compliant multi-document transactions and a JavaScript-based computational model, ensuring strong consistency and providing massive parallelism.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<b>RIGA, LATVIA — October 8, 2015</b> — <a href="http://www.clusterpoint.com/">Clusterpoint</a>, a database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS), today announced the availability of Clusterpoint 4, an evolution of its database software now becoming a computing engine. This unique platform combines an instantly scalable document-oriented database and computing so businesses can process and analyze large amounts of data in real-time at a reasonable cost.\r\n\r\nBecause datasets are much bigger today than what can be stored in the memory of a single server, businesses are looking beyond traditional relational databases, which no longer provide the right computational platform for today’s “big data” computing needs. Moreover, businesses today want to do more than access information in a static format; they want to analyze and transform their data to gain valuable insights about their business quickly and cost effectively.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint 4 solves these data challenge by unifying computational power and data. Clusterpoint has built a distributed cloud computer that can share data among multiple computational nodes and execute code on those nodes next to the data. Furthermore, because Clusterpoint 4 was designed as a complete relational database replacement for businesses today, they built a new data manipulation and querying language in JS/SQL. JavaScript, a universal non-proprietary language, now can be utilized for data retrieval and data transformation in a familiar SQL structure. This truly makes Clusterpoint a computing engine that can not only store data, but process data and run arbitrary computations.\r\n\r\nThe Clusterpoint 4 Computing Engine was built on top of Clusterpoint 3, creating a distributed document-oriented database that supports persisting data structures while building efficient numeric, full-text and geospatial indices.\r\n\r\nTo be considered a real replacement for relational databases, Clusterpoint 4 supports ACID-compliant multi-document transactions and a rich computational model based on JavaScript — two features often ignored by other NoSQL databases in the market today. For many use cases it’s imperative to work on multiple data objects within one transaction to guarantee immediate consistency. Another important aspect of the database is its computational capabilities. The Clusterpoint 4 API is based on the concept that a database needs to allow arbitrary computation to be done on the data inside of the database. This allows various stages of retrieval to use arbitrary JavaScript code to transform the data. Additionally, JavaScript code accesses indices instead of raw objects, providing greater efficiency.\r\n\r\n“With Clusterpoint 4, we want to reduce complexity and costs of existing IT infrastructure and enable real-time processing of data on a massive scale. We want our users, like developers, to import their raw data and then leverage the power of our computing engine to transform that data into something that has business benefits, exactly when and how they want it,” said Zigmars Raascevskis, CEO of Clusterpoint.\r\n\r\nUtilizing the Clusterpoint Cloud, users can scale instantly and get on-demand computational resources at a millisecond granularity. In addition, businesses benefit from a unique pricing model -- a true pay-per-use model that is disrupting the tiered pricing model of today’s traditional Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS) offerings — which no other DBAAS company provides.\r\n\r\nFor more detailed information about Clusterpoint 4, please visit their blog.\r\n<h2>About Clusterpoint</h2>\r\nClusterpoint is a database vendor providing Database-As-A-Service (DBAAS) for developers and small to medium size businesses worldwide that want instant scalability and massive distributed computing power for their growing database needs but without the hefty price tag. Founded in 2006, Clusterpoint has served business customers as an enterprise-oriented NoSQL database. Today the Clusterpoint database is used across different industries to drive 24/7 mission-critical web and mobile application solutions. For more information about our cloud-based service, visit <a href="http://www.clusterpoint.com/">www.clusterpoint.com</a>.\r\n<h2>Contact:</h2>\r\nJohn Conrad\r\nMerritt Group\r\n<a href="tel:703-390-1538">703-390-1538</a>', 'Clusterpoint Disrupts Cloud Database Market with Clusterpoint 4 Computing Engine Combining Instantly Scalable Database and Computational Power', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'clusterpoint-disrupts-cloud-database-market-with-clusterpoint-4-computing-engine-combining-instantly-scalable-database-and-computational-power', '', '', '2016-02-25 16:21:42', '2016-02-25 14:21:42', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?post_type=press_releases&#038;p=173', 3, 'press_releases', '', 0),
(179, 1, '2016-01-29 10:11:29', '2016-01-29 08:11:29', 'With 2016 now upon us, it''s a good idea to take stock of the growing world of NoSQL. As organizations battle in today''s modern economy, weaning actionable business information out of the massive amounts of data generated through social media and other sources offers a real competitive advantage. This competition is a main driver fuelling the increasing adoption rates of a wide array of NoSQL databases, including <a href="https://www.clusterpoint.com/blog/the-top-5-reasons-to-use-clusterpoint" target="_blank">Clusterpoint</a>.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThat''s not to say there aren''t any altruistic applications where the use of a NoSQL database offers benefits. Many interesting use-cases exist in a variety of industries. This article looks at some of the more promising anticipated trends in NoSQL usage over the next year.\r\n<h2>Noting the Entry of NoSQL into the Technology Mainstream</h2>\r\nIn an article on the <a href="http://www.information-age.com/technology/information-management/123460615/top-8-trends-big-data-2016" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">top Big Data trends for 2016</a>, Information Age noted the increasing acceptance of NoSQL technology at many enterprises'' IT shops. The magazine observed the DBMS "Magic Quadrant" produced by the industry analyst group, Gartner, now features a host of NoSQL companies (MarkLogic, DataStax, etc.) in addition to the usual stalwarts like Oracle, IBM, and SAP. The magazine predicts the traditional database vendors will soon be outnumbered by their NoSQL brethren.\r\n\r\nAnother prediction for 2016 from Information Age relates to increased enterprise adoption of the Apache Hadoop framework. Part of this is driven by new technologies used in concert with Hadoop that offer enhanced role-based authentication and security (Apache Sentry) and new options for OLAP. The latter is especially noteworthy considering the growing role of the data scientist at many companies.\r\n<h2>Structured Query Language is not going Anywhere</h2>\r\nEven as NoSQL databases become more prevalent in the industry, that doesn''t mean the venerable Structured Query Language is going away anytime soon. In fact, the online magazine, insideBIGDATA, predicted SQL will become the <a href="http://insidebigdata.com/2015/12/29/the-top-3-big-data-trends-of-2016/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">preeminent query language</a> for NoSQL Big Data applications in 2016. It was one of the magazine''s three Big Data trends for the upcoming year.\r\n\r\nSo, if you are wizard with a WHERE clause, rest assured your skills will remain in demand for the foreseeable future. The latest version of Clusterpoint features a computing engine that allows queries to be written using a combination of SQL and JavaScript. SQL veterans are able to leverage their experience building powerful queries to retrieve, store, and transform data.\r\n<h2>Java''s Decline is NoSQL''s Gain</h2>\r\nMany technology pundits have noticed the decline of Java as an enterprise development language, including Moumita Adhikary in <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/java-dead-end-enterprise-app-development-moumita-adhikary" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">an article</a> published on LinkedIn Pulse. While Java developers are still in demand overall, there is a notable shift to maintenance positions among those job openings. Is Java slated to become the COBOL of the 21st Century?\r\n\r\nThe reasons for the decline of Java in the enterprise are numerous. A notable one relevant to this article is the growth of systems built around NoSQL databases using a variety of newer languages. As noted earlier, Clusterpoint offers support for its own JavaScript/SQL computing engine, which is callable from PHP and other web development languages.\r\n<h2>In-Memory Data Stores offer Speed for NoSQL Processing</h2>\r\nJoe McKendrick, for Database Trends and Applications, <a href="http://www.dbta.com/Editorial/Trends-and-Applications/16-Trends-Reshaping-the-Enterprise-Data-Landscape-in-2016-107911.aspx" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">predicts an increase</a> in the use of in-memory data stores in 2016. When considering the growing importance of real-time analytics -- another one of McKendrick''s 2016 trends -- in-memory architectures offer a significant speed advantage over their disk-based counterparts. This additional processing horsepower is vital for enterprises truly wanting to leverage their investments in NoSQL databases.\r\n\r\nClusterpoint''s own DBaaS Cloud-based architecture takes advantage of in-memory data stores to provide the speed and computing power necessary for businesses to extract the valuable information contained within their data. Speaking of the Cloud, McKendrick also foresees additional growth over the next year in the use of Cloud services for data analytics applications. Considering the complex, distributed architectures used in the DBaaS model -- including Clusterpoint -- disk-based data storage is essentially becoming obsolete.\r\n<h2>The Time for NoSQL is Now</h2>\r\nHopefully, this look at a few of the more interesting NoSQL trends for the upcoming year provided some insight into the growth of NoSQL at enterprises and even smaller businesses as well. While the venerable relational database still has its place in some applications, the rapid growth of Cloud-based distributed architectures, eCommerce, social media, and other aspects of the modern economy require something that operates in real time.\r\n\r\nExpect NoSQL-based applications to continue to cement their status as enterprise-worthy solutions over the next twelve months and beyond.\r\n\r\nBy Paul Williams\r\nEditor at <a href="http://tabmuse.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">TabMuse.com</a>', 'NoSQL Trends for 2016', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'nosql-trends-for-2016', '', '', '2016-02-26 10:12:43', '2016-02-26 08:12:43', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?p=179', 2, 'post', '', 0),
(180, 1, '2016-02-11 10:13:45', '2016-02-11 08:13:45', 'When working with operational databases, speed and flexibility are critical assets for both the database architecture itself and the underlying infrastructure.\r\n<h2>New Database Architectures Support <i>Bigger</i> Data</h2>\r\nBut speed and flexibility cannot be achieved by simply throwing more resources at working environments. Relational algebraic solutions like RDBMS and NoSQL are limited by their inability to perform compute functions internally, which means they have to rely on external resources that are often separated by distance and require an array of protocols and proprietary formats to communicate. Indeed, the very reason that most organizations feel the need to deploy Hadoop, MapReduce and other targeted Big Data solutions is because their traditional database architectures cannot cope with high volumes of data.\r\n<h2>The Rise of Clusterpoint Computing Engine &amp; JS/SQL</h2>\r\nThis is why Clusterpoint combines computational capabilities with the data store to create a fully scalable compute engine. Not only does this provide a solid foundation to support large data loads, it provides a highly flexible means to implement rapid analytics processes.\r\n\r\nTraditional SQL solutions are optimized primarily for tabular data, but document-oriented databases like Clusterpoint use JSON or XML objects within a hierarchical structure. In order to drive compute directly to the database, ClusterPoint’s JavaScript/SQL (JS/SQL) querying language places a JavaScript layer on top of the basic SQL building block. This allows virtually any computation to be performed with any query, providing a highly flexible and powerful means of transforming data within the database. This is already a popular practice on front-end database solutions and is starting to make its presence known on the back-end at the node level. As well, JavaScript works very well with JSON by translating it into native objects.\r\n\r\nJS/SQL allows for arbitrary JavaScript commands to be placed in any clause within the SELECT and UPDATE statements. For example, within the SET clause of the UPDATE statement, JavaScript code can be used to deserialize a document as an object, which can then be modified arbitrarily – perhaps to create a new field with a new value calculated from data elsewhere in the document. By executing this function within the database, we can manage the entire process from a single request.\r\n\r\nAs well, within the SELECT statement, we can insert selected results of a particular document so that it becomes an entirely new document. This is very useful when attempting to apply auto-generated IDs to individual shards, and dramatically lowers inter-cluster traffic as well.\r\n<h2>Benefits of New Database Architecture: Flexibility &amp; Speed</h2>\r\nThe practical benefits of this are multi-fold. For one, by transforming data within the database using an arbitrary JavaScript core it becomes easier to work on multiple data objects within a single transaction, all while maintaining a high degree of consistency. At the same time, it allows for various stages of retrieval using indices, rather than raw objects, to enable greater efficiency and support real-time or near-real-time analytics.\r\n\r\nThis approach also produces a dramatic improvement in speed, so much so that it is not unreasonable to start thinking about JavaScript execution supporting the fastest databases ever created. Utilizing a V8 JavaScript engine, we can quickly compile code and execute computations, but we inevitably run into delays reading from disk, deserializing from JSON to JavaScript and then running JS expressions on top of every operation.\r\n\r\nJS/SQL makes JavaScript think it is accessing raw objects from a data store but in reality is accessing a C++ function that interacts with indices optimized for in-memory or SSD access. As well, the Clusterpoint platform utilizes query optimization techniques to ensure that indices are accessed to narrow down the set of documents on which JavaScript is invoked. Clusterpoint also uses the SQL structure to run query executions in parallel and distribute individual computational tasks across multiple nodes in a cluster.\r\n<h2>How JS/SQL Query Works</h2>\r\n<b>So a basic JS/SQL query execution process consists of three key steps: </b>\r\na) Clusterpoint figures out a query plan involving distributed parallelized execution of the query,\r\nb) JS expressions are compiled to machine code on each computational node, which accesses the involved fields through indices,\r\nc) Data is gathered back, aggregated and returned to the user.\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nDirect execution of JavaScript is a key step in Clusterpoint’s evolution from database software to full-fledged compute engine. At the moment, most enterprises are looking to operational database platforms to help find hidden patterns and unseen connections within and between data. But it won’t be long before organizations will see the need not just to analyze data but transform it to gain even more valuable insights into their businesses and overall industries.\r\n\r\nBy supporting JavaScript execution within the database, the enterprise will gain a highly efficient, highly scalable means of assessing business conditions not only as they are now, but how they could be with just a few little changes.\r\n\r\nBy Jurgis Orups\r\nCTO at Clusterpoint', 'The Advantages of Executing JavaScript in the Clusterpoint Database', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-advantages-of-executing-javascript-in-the-clusterpoint-database', '', '', '2016-02-26 10:14:49', '2016-02-26 08:14:49', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?p=180', 1, 'post', '', 0),
(146, 1, '2016-02-15 12:33:38', '2016-02-15 10:33:38', '<div class="page" title="Page 15">\r\n<div class="section">\r\n<div class="layoutArea">\r\n<div class="column">\r\n\r\nSupport of the transactions consisting of the set of multiple operations is one of the key features of Clusterpoint database server software. It means that in one transaction it is possible to change multiple documents. Transactions are one or more operations that all must succeed. If one operation fails, all the other operations in transaction fail as well, and the database is reversed to the state before the transaction began.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 'Transaction mechanism in Clusterpoint database', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'transaction-mechanism-in-clusterpoint-database', '', '', '2016-02-15 12:33:38', '2016-02-15 10:33:38', '', 0, 'https://newwww.clusterpoint.com/wp/?post_type=press_white_papers&#038;p=146', 0, 'press_white_papers', '', 0),
